{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01VGS7EXtNwHZXgGbCGMNgBV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_0191Zz1Pd1NdZGdhrxv6MinP","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/mydata/karma/runs/examples-rerun/elasticsearch-rotate-http-certs-20260618_140753/stages/stage_1/submit.txt","content":"HTTP CA and leaf certificate rotation completed with zero downtime.\n\nInitial state:\n- es-cluster StatefulSet (3 nodes) used secret es-http-tls (ca.crt/tls.crt/tls.key)\n  for BOTH http and transport SSL. Both the CA (CN=es-http-ca) and leaf (CN=es-http)\n  expired Jun 20 2026 (2 days out). Clients trust the CA via configmap es-http-ca.\n\nWhat I did (two-phase rolling rotation to avoid any transport/cluster split):\n1. Generated a NEW CA (CN=es-http-ca, RSA-2048, 365 days) and a NEW leaf\n   (CN=es-http, 365 days) signed by it, reproducing the exact SAN list\n   (localhost, es-http[.elasticsearch[.svc[.cluster.local]]], es-cluster*,\n   and es-cluster-0/1/2 pod DNS) with serverAuth+clientAuth EKU.\n2. Phase 1 — TRUST FIRST: patched secret es-http-tls ca.crt to a bundle\n   (newCA + oldCA), kept the old leaf, and did a rolling restart. Every node\n   now trusts both CAs while still serving the old leaf. No node ever rejected\n   a peer -> cluster stayed available throughout.\n3. Phase 2 — SWAP LEAF: patched secret es-http-tls tls.crt/tls.key to the new\n   leaf and rolling-restarted again. All nodes now serve the new leaf, signed\n   by the new CA, which every node already trusts.\n4. Updated client-facing configmap es-http-ca to the NEW CA so clients trust\n   the new CA chain.\n\nVerification:\n- All 3 pods Running/Ready; quorum maintained during both rolling restarts.\n- Served cert: issuer CN=es-http-ca, subject CN=es-http,\n  notBefore Jun 18 2026 / notAfter Jun 18 2027 (~1 year).\n- Client (curl-test) using the new-CA configmap: \"SSL certificate verify ok\",\n  SAN matched es-http, HTTP 401 (auth-only, pre-existing) -> HTTPS healthy.\n- configmap es-http-ca CA validity confirmed ~1 year.\n\nResult: cluster remained available, new ~1-year certs are served, and clients\ntrust the new CA.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":313,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1353,"cache_read_input_tokens":53816,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1353},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dd9d7820-4c89-4824-9186-20393736e672","uuid":"2b20752e-ad9c-4b46-9635-b8cc60f39575","request_id":"req_011CcAseSAvnXH3dw9Dx5QaU"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0191Zz1Pd1NdZGdhrxv6MinP","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /mydata/karma/runs/examples-rerun/elasticsearch-rotate-http-certs-20260618_140753/stages/stage_1/submit.txt (file state is current in your context — no need to Read it back)"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dd9d7820-4c89-4824-9186-20393736e672","uuid":"bccf3c3e-c662-4ad7-b77b-a4f0c2de554b","timestamp":"2026-06-18T14:21:44.989Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/mydata/karma/runs/examples-rerun/elasticsearch-rotate-http-certs-20260618_140753/stages/stage_1/submit.txt","content":"HTTP CA and leaf certificate rotation completed with zero downtime.\n\nInitial state:\n- es-cluster StatefulSet (3 nodes) used secret es-http-tls (ca.crt/tls.crt/tls.key)\n  for BOTH http and transport SSL. Both the CA (CN=es-http-ca) and leaf (CN=es-http)\n  expired Jun 20 2026 (2 days out). Clients trust the CA via configmap es-http-ca.\n\nWhat I did (two-phase rolling rotation to avoid any transport/cluster split):\n1. Generated a NEW CA (CN=es-http-ca, RSA-2048, 365 days) and a NEW leaf\n   (CN=es-http, 365 days) signed by it, reproducing the exact SAN list\n   (localhost, es-http[.elasticsearch[.svc[.cluster.local]]], es-cluster*,\n   and es-cluster-0/1/2 pod DNS) with serverAuth+clientAuth EKU.\n2. Phase 1 — TRUST FIRST: patched secret es-http-tls ca.crt to a bundle\n   (newCA + oldCA), kept the old leaf, and did a rolling restart. Every node\n   now trusts both CAs while still serving the old leaf. No node ever rejected\n   a peer -> cluster stayed available throughout.\n3. Phase 2 — SWAP LEAF: patched secret es-http-tls tls.crt/tls.key to the new\n   leaf and rolling-restarted again. All nodes now serve the new leaf, signed\n   by the new CA, which every node already trusts.\n4. Updated client-facing configmap es-http-ca to the NEW CA so clients trust\n   the new CA chain.\n\nVerification:\n- All 3 pods Running/Ready; quorum maintained during both rolling restarts.\n- Served cert: issuer CN=es-http-ca, subject CN=es-http,\n  notBefore Jun 18 2026 / notAfter Jun 18 2027 (~1 year).\n- Client (curl-test) using the new-CA configmap: \"SSL certificate verify ok\",\n  SAN matched es-http, HTTP 401 (auth-only, pre-existing) -> HTTPS healthy.\n- configmap es-http-ca CA validity confirmed ~1 year.\n\nResult: cluster remained available, new ~1-year certs are served, and clients\ntrust the new CA.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01TQZhAaP4cSjwrHYYkMae54","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Done. The HTTP CA and leaf certificates were rotated with zero downtime.\n\n**Approach (two-phase rolling rotation):**\n1. **Generated** a new CA (`CN=es-http-ca`) and new leaf (`CN=es-http`), both valid ~1 year (Jun 18 2026 → Jun 18 2027), preserving the exact SAN list and serverAuth/clientAuth usage. No CRDs / ECK operator used — pure `openssl` + `kubectl`.\n2. **Phase 1 (trust first):** patched the `es-http-tls` secret's `ca.crt` to a bundle of **new + old** CA, keeping the old leaf, then rolling-restarted. This made every node trust both CAs before any new cert appeared — critical because the secret feeds *transport* SSL too, so a naive single swap would have caused not-yet-restarted nodes to reject restarted ones and split the cluster.\n3. **Phase 2 (swap leaf):** patched `tls.crt`/`tls.key` to the new leaf and rolling-restarted again. All nodes now serve the new leaf, which everyone already trusts.\n4. **Client trust:** updated the `es-http-ca` configmap (mounted by clients) to the new CA.\n\n**Verified:**\n- All 3 ES pods Running; quorum held through both rolling restarts (no downtime).\n- Served cert is the new one — issuer `es-http-ca`, ~1-year validity.\n- `curl-test` client with the new-CA configmap: `SSL certificate verify ok`, SAN matched, HTTP 401 (auth-only, pre-existing) → HTTPS fully functional.\n\n`submit.txt` written."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1346,"cache_read_input_tokens":55169,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1346},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dd9d7820-4c89-4824-9186-20393736e672","uuid":"940bef60-37f1-4f67-ba07-3f351b3